Fig. 9
 shows that the FL of Zr-N-CDs was quenched to a certain extent (red) in the presence of 55 µM Cr(VI) and Cr(III) mixture because only Cr(VI) can quench the FL of CDs. Based on the above method, the quenching efficiency of CDs increased (blue) when Cr(III) was transformed to Cr(VI). Moreover, the Cr that formed in different water samples (tap water, lake water, and well water) was investigated to verify the scientificity of the proposed method (Table 2
). Based on the above results, Zr-N-CDs can identify Cr(VI) and Cr(III) in water samples effectively through a simple experimental process.
